snippet.textDisplay: Cool, but the conclusion is substantially incorrect. There are way more than 7 holes in the human body at birth. A few extra that come up to my mind (I'm sure there are more) are the loop created by the ear bones and various tendons in the middle ear (you could run inside the eustachian tube from the nasal cavity till you reach the middle ear, then pass behind the incus, that creates a freestanding closed loop with the stapes, and come back to the nasal cavity, which accounts for an extra hole per ear); the various pathways contributing to the so-called "collateral ventilation" in the lungs (like the channels of Martin, channels of Lambert and pores of Kohn (which okay, technically start forming only after birth, but still...) that interconnect neighboring alveoli and bronchioli in the lungs, making them topologically homeomorphic with a sponge rather than a bunch of grapes; or the hymen, that at birth might present more than one perforation (split or cribriform hymen)...
